# 1. Repo clone
git clone git@github.com:your-org/otel-tempo-quickstart.git
cd otel-tempo-quickstart

# 2. Env file create
cp .env.example .env
nano .env   # password change, retention adjust, etc.

# 3. Script executable
chmod +x setup.sh

# 4. Stack up
./setup.sh

# 5. Status check
./setup.sh --status




















































































---------------------------------------------------------------------------



## Option 1 (Recommended): Use Docker’s official repository

This avoids weirdness with mirrors and gives you the latest Docker + Compose. ([Docker Documentation][1])

Run these commands in your VM:

```bash
# 0. Remove any half-installed old Docker bits (safe to run)
sudo apt remove -y docker docker.io docker-doc docker-compose docker-compose-plugin containerd runc

# 1. Update packages
sudo apt update

# 2. Install prerequisites
sudo apt install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg

# 3. Add Docker’s official GPG key
sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg

# 4. Add Docker’s APT repo (for jammy)
echo \
  "deb [arch=$(dpkg --print-architecture) signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] \
  https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu \
  $(. /etc/os-release && echo "$VERSION_CODENAME") stable" \
  | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list > /dev/null

# 5. Update again so apt sees the new repo
sudo apt update

# 6. Install Docker Engine + CLI + Buildx + Compose plugin + git
sudo apt install -y git docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io \
  docker-buildx-plugin docker-compose-plugin
```

Now create the docker group (if it isn’t there) and add your user:

```bash
sudo groupadd docker 2>/dev/null || true
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
exit
vagrant ssh obs-vm   # group change effect
```

Log out of the VM and back in (or run `newgrp docker`) so your new group membership is active, then test:

```bash
docker --version
docker compose version
docker run hello-world
```

You should see valid versions and the hello-world container should run.



